Example: Counter
The counter example has emerged as one of the most basic examples for showcasing state management tools. Here we go:
Basic Counter
import React from &apos;react&apos;
import { createStore } from &apos;react-woodworm&apos;

const model = 0
const actions {
  increment: state =&gt; state + 1,
  decrement: state =&gt; state - 1
}

const { Provider, Consumer } = createStore({
  model,
  actions
})

const Counter = () =&gt; (
  &lt;Provider&gt;
    &lt;Consumer&gt;
      {({ state, actions }) =&gt; (
        &lt;div&gt;
          &lt;div&gt;{state}&lt;/div&gt;
          &lt;button onClick={actions.increment}&gt;+&lt;/button&gt;
          &lt;button onClick={actions.decrement}&gt;-&lt;/button&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
      )}
    &lt;/Consumer&gt;
  &lt;/Provider&gt;
)

Dynamic Steps
Instead of always incrementing or decrementing by one, we can also pass a step value to e.g. increment by 5.
import React from &apos;react&apos;
import { createStore } from &apos;react-woodworm&apos;

const model = 0
const actions {
  increment: state =&gt; state + 1,
  decrement: state =&gt; state - 1,
  incrementBy: (state, step) =&gt; state + step,
  decrementBy: (state, step) =&gt; state - step
}

const { Provider, Consumer } = createStore({
  model,
  actions
})

const Counter = () =&gt; (
  &lt;Provider&gt;
    &lt;Consumer&gt;
      {({ state, actions }) =&gt; (
        &lt;div&gt;
          &lt;div&gt;{state}&lt;/div&gt;
          &lt;button onClick={actions.increment}&gt;+&lt;/button&gt;
          &lt;button onClick={actions.decrement}&gt;-&lt;/button&gt;
          &lt;button onClick={() =&gt; actions.incrementBy(5)}&gt;+5&lt;/button&gt;
          &lt;button onClick={() =&gt; actions.decrementBy(5)}&gt;-5&lt;/button&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
      )}
    &lt;/Consumer&gt;
  &lt;/Provider&gt;
)

Asynchronous Steps
Apart from triggering state changes through user interaction, we can also use effects to trigger changes asynchronously e.g. after a given delay.
import React from &apos;react&apos;
import { createStore } from &apos;react-woodworm&apos;

const model = 0
const actions {
  increment: state =&gt; state + 1,
  decrement: state =&gt; state - 1
}
const effects = {
  incrementAfter: (actions, delay) =&gt; setTimeout(actions.increment, delay)
}

const { Provider, Consumer } = createStore({
  model,
  actions,
  effects
})

const Counter = () =&gt; (
  &lt;Provider&gt;
    &lt;Consumer&gt;
      {({ state, actions, effects }) =&gt; (
        &lt;div&gt;
          &lt;div&gt;{state}&lt;/div&gt;
          &lt;button onClick={actions.increment}&gt;+&lt;/button&gt;
          &lt;button onClick={actions.decrement}&gt;-&lt;/button&gt;
          &lt;button onClick={() =&gt; effects.incrementAfter(1000)}&gt;+ (delayed 1s)&lt;/button&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
      )}
    &lt;/Consumer&gt;
  &lt;/Provider&gt;
)

docs/api/Provider.html.body:
Provider
The Provider component keeps an instance of the store and provides it to all nested Consumer components.
Props



Property
Type
Description




initialState
(any?)
An initial state unique to this Provider instance. It overwrites the global model.



Example
import { createStore } from &apos;react-woodworm&apos;

const model = 0
const actions = {
  increment: state =&gt; state + 1,
  decrement: state =&gt; state - 1
}

const CounterStore = createStore({
  actions,
  model
})

const Counter = () =&gt; (
  &lt;CounterStore.Provider&gt;
    &lt;CounterStore.Consumer&gt;
      {state =&gt; state}
    &lt;/CounterStore.Consumer&gt;
  &lt;/CounterStore.Provider&gt;
)

Using initialState
The following example with start the counter from 10 instead of 0.
const StartFrom10 = () =&gt; (
  &lt;CounterStore.Provider initialState={10}&gt;
    &lt;CounterStore.Consumer&gt;
      {state =&gt; state}
    &lt;/CounterStore.Consumer&gt;
  &lt;/CounterStore.Provider&gt;
)

docs/api/Consumer.html.body:
Consumer
The Consumer component is used to access  state, actions and effects from the closest Provider component.
It provides a render-prop interface that passes a single object containing state, actions and effects to the render function.

It must be wrapped by at least one Provider component or else it throws an error.

Example
import { createStore } from &apos;react-woodworm&apos;

const model = 0
const actions = {
  increment: state =&gt; state + 1,
  decrement: state =&gt; state - 1
}

const Counter = createStore({
  actions,
  model
})

const renderCounter = ({ state, actions }) =&gt; (
  &lt;div&gt;
    &lt;div&gt;Counter: {state}
    &lt;button onClick={actions.increment}&gt;+&lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;button onClick={actions.decrement}&gt;-&lt;/button&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
)

const SimpleCounter = () =&gt; (
  &lt;Counter.Provider&gt;
    &lt;Counter.Consumer&gt;{renderCounter}&lt;/Counter.Consumer&gt;
  &lt;/Counter.Provider&gt;
)
